diacoustics.d:
n. That branch of natural philosophy which treats of the
   properties of sound as affected by passing through different mediums;
   -- called also diaphonics. See the Note under Acoustics.

difform.d:
a. Irregular in form; -- opposed to uniform; anomalous;
   hence, unlike; dissimilar; as, to difform corolla, the parts of which
   do not correspond in size or proportion; difform leaves.

diffuseness.d:
n. The quality of being diffuse; especially, in writing,
   the use of a great or excessive number of word to express the meaning;
   copiousness; verbosity; prolixity.

diffusiveness.d:
n. The quality or state of being diffusive or diffuse;
   extensiveness; expansion; dispersion. Especially of style: Diffuseness;
   want of conciseness; prolixity.

dioptrical.d:
a. Of or pertaining to dioptrics; assisting vision by
   means of the refraction of light; refractive; as, the dioptric system;
   a dioptric glass or telescope.

disallowances.d:
plural of disallowance
n. The act of disallowing; refusal to admit or permit;
   rejection.

disanimation.d:
n. Privation of life.
n. The state of being disanimated or discouraged;
   depression of spirits.

disperse.d:
v. to cause to separate and go in different directions
v. move away from each other; 
v. separate (light) into spectral rays

disposure.d:
n. The act of disposing; power to dispose of; disposal;
   direction.
n. Disposition; arrangement; position; posture.

disrelish.d:
n. Want of relish; dislike (of the palate or of the mind);
   distaste; a slight degree of disgust; as, a disrelish for some kinds of
   food.
n. Absence of relishing or palatable quality; bad taste;
   nauseousness.
v. t. Not to relish; to regard as unpalatable or offensive;
   to feel a degree of disgust at.
v. t. To deprive of relish; to make nauseous or disgusting
   in a slight degree.

dissoluteness.d:
n. State or quality of being dissolute; looseness of
   morals and manners; addictedness to sinful pleasures; debauchery;
   dissipation.
